title: After seeing the NEET 2020 paper, what advice would you give to an aspirant writing NEET 2021 or NEET 2022? - Quora

response.answer_text: I personally have seen the rapid ‘transition’ in the pre-medical exams from the student’s perspective. (From AIPMT 2015 to NEET 2020, from when I was in class 11th, to now, being a 2nd Year MBBS Student at MAMC) There is an academic and a non-academic part as the answer to this question. I'll first answer the latter one. I've seen people with same marks, one admitted in one of the top Medical colleges in India and the other one struggling for even getting an MBBS seat, but in different year. Earlier around 550 marks were considered more than enough for ‘guaranteeing’ a decent medical college in Delhi (through State Quota) and 590+ marks were labeled as ‘excellent’ performance and people congratulated him/her even before the results that “ MAMC to Pakka hai” (Getting MAMC is confirmed) (Comparing with the previous year cut-offs) So, because of this, the teachers planned a simple strategy/ MANTRA for the students to ‘ensure’ their selection in NEET - “30 questions. These are the number of questions you can leave in the exam. You don't need to attempt full paper.” 5 from Biology 10 from Chemistry 15 from Physics (which usually was/is the most feared subject among aspirants) “Any doubt regarding any answer during the exam, put that question into this category and move forward. Just try attempting a minimum of 150 questions with utmost precision and accuracy. What were the benefits of this strategy? Least chance of getting ‘negatives’, since we've not attempted the ones with doubt or which was difficult. Getting 570 (with 30 negatives) instead of 600, even though getting the same number of questions correct in both case, hurts and can be the deciding factor between you and your dream college.Students would get a decent score around 600, if they are precise enough. And even if they had some incorrect answers, there was a huge window of 50 marks (10 questions getting wrong) from the decent score of 550. So their chances of selection was way more!So, it was a really good plan and it did even work for many students who gave AIPMT 2015 and NEET 2016 and they are currently doing/did their MBBS from excellent institutions. The students who were supposed to give the exam in 2017 also decided to use this strategy in their main exam as well. But little did they know about the huge spike in the total number of students appearing for NEET 2017 (almost getting tripled to 11.4 lakhs from 4 lakh in NEET 2016) which lead to increase in competition and surprisingly the number of people scoring 600+ increased and the ones scoring 550+ (All over India) grew exponentially because of the influx. Because of this, many students who were following the strategy mentioned above barely got an MBBS seat (through 2nd/Mop-up round through All India Quota) and there were many who didn't even get a seat even after scoring the ‘decent’ 550s. As a result, more number of students started to ‘stretch’ themselves in order to get more marks than before and the number of students with excellent preparation increased which lead to increase in competition every year. The main point which I am trying to tell is - The time has come where student should start aiming for a perfect 720 , the maximum marks which they ‘can’ get instead of just aiming for a particular range which they consider as ‘Safe’ after seeing the previous year cut-off for that college. Even the ones who are getting their marks in 200s, 300s, 400s should also start aiming for a perfect 720 during their preparation with a positive attitude to maximize their marks because I'm seeing the people with 250s marks last year getting 600+ this year. So, nothing is impossible if you have the will to do it, because we have the proof in front of our eyes! That's it! Now talking about the academic part of the answer. There is nothing new about the advice about this part. It remains the same, which is constantly given from the beginning to every NEET aspirant : Firstly, you should be thorough with NCERT since almost 95% questions (or more) are made on the basis of the information inside it. (Reading too much additional material only but not to be able to answer direct questions from NCERT is completely ‘illegal’)And Secondly, just prepare yourself for the worst (Every teacher's favorite dialog)Expanding your knowledge a bit about the topics and probably strengthening your concepts, isn't harmful. Some of you might think - “Aren't these two points exactly opposite?” No Buddy! Frankly speaking, the truth is, the ones who are able to completely read, understand and implement these two points (which are frequently taught by most teachers) successfully, are the ones getting ‘selected’ in NEET every year. I personally have encountered many students (3rd/4th drop) in my drop year , who were just busy cramming irrelevant facts whole year, and didn't know basic NCERT facts and getting them wrong in the institute tests, for which some were (literally) scolded by the teachers for getting them wrong especially in the Biology section. There is a reason why it is considered as the ‘Holy Book’ for the NEET aspirants. And for Physics and chemistry as well, the points remain the same but there is no harm in pushing your limits to do JEE- level questions as well, since you have to be prepared for the worst. This year the students were lucky that most of the questions were ‘direct’ and very few were twisted. This is not gonna happen every year, if you're lucky, it might, but not every year! You can go through this answer for a clearer view regarding the same. Abhishek Garg's answer to Why is it found that most of the NEET and AIIMS toppers do JEE level books for preparing chemistry and physics? Is this is the real "success mantra" of them? And my final advice to all the future NEET aspirants is that - Do write the JEE Main exam even if you haven't opted for mathematics in your 11th & 12th class (They verify that only at the time of counseling not before) . Since it is conducted before the NEET exam every year, it is the best option for you to get the feel of a national entrance exam conducted by the same body as that of yours and is more or less the same difficulty, if your concepts are clear. (You have 3 hours for 60 questions of Physics and Chemistry [Now it is 25 questions each] ) That's it. These would be some of my advices to the future NEET aspirants! All the best for your preparation! And feel free to share your opinions regarding the points as well! Signing Off A.G

A2A. If I have to be brutally honest, NEET 2019 and 2020 , both of which have been conducted by NTA, are extremely easy compared to the erstwhile papers that CBSE used to set. Probably the best paper in recent years was NEET 2018 which was coincidentally the last paper set by CBSE, before NTA took over. The sort of paper that NTA makes, merely tests your ability to recall lines from NCERT, with a very trivial importance being given to actual problem solving and lateral thinking. Now wether this is good / bad isn't for me to decide / comment on. But what it does indicate is that the importance of NCERT is growing immensely with each year. You have to be thorough with it if you aspire for an MBBS seat. But this also doesn't mean that one merely goes about memorising stuff without understanding it. That's hazardous. Understand it, relate it. If you do that then you can easily reproduce it in your paper. (Some things have to be mugged up though, just to be clear). And do give importance to reducing the so called silly mistakes, that one attributes to inadequacy of time, wrong OMR marking, brain fades and what not. How to overcome that? By practicing and analysing, and not making the same mistakes again. You understand the importance of each mark when there are 500–600 people on the same marks but having varying ranks. I have often regretted it, but ultimately it's not something I can change. So be clear with your concepts, NCERT, and avoid silly mistakes by increasing your accuracy. Hope for the best, be prepared for the worst, and take what comes. Good Luck 👍.

I have appeared for both NEET-2019 and NEET-2020 so I consider myself eligible to write this answer. Now most of the people know that 'paper NCERT se hi ata h' but I would like to suggest you something more.. After seeing the level of the paper many students are going to limit themselves to easy Questions but please don't do this mistake. Do solve every type (hard , medium, easy, tricky etc…)of Questions, it helps in broadening your mind.Keep your goals high..I will say keep a target of 720(I am not joking). You never know what will happen next year.Be prepared for every type of paper , prepare for the worst i.e easiest to toughest. (Because you can’t generalise anything )Keep yourself mentally healthy and calm. I have learnt this recently that mental peace was important than anything this year because of covid-19 and delayed exam.If you dare to dream then work hard for it. Nothing comes easy.And I wish you luck because now I feel 'Luck matters'. Have a good day ^_^

I just gave the NEET exam on 13th September and so I guess I am eligible to write the answer. After seeing this year’s paper it’s very clear that NTA heavily supports NCERT. Almost all questions in Bio, inorganic chemistry and organic chemistry were from ncert. Also Physics was very easy mostly putting values in the formula and finding answer same was the case with physical chemistry. Also focus on conceptual questions in physics as they comprised a major part of the physics paper. So, all my fellow juniors I would request you to understand and revise NCERT multiple times and most importantly work on your accuracy which is really important when question paper is easy to avoid silly mistakes. And finally Best of luck to all NEET aspirants.

So I am myself a neet aspirant (right now studying in 11) I don't think we should decide by seeing this year papers because it was corona time and NTA must have given easy paper. Well,in my coaching my teacher has told that difficulty of paper will increase somehow , so it is better to make foundation strong and not take paper easely and prepare fully like everybody used to do. So,best of luck Future doctors

Hope for the Best, but Prepare for the Worst. Don't drop the intensity of your preparation, otherwise dropping marks will hurt badly. READ NCERT OF NOT JUST BIOLOGY BUT PHYSICS AND CHEMISTRY TOO. Don't ignore NCERT.
